<h5>
Presentation 2: Australian perceptions of the benefits and barriers to
vegetarian diets
</h5>

<p>
Authors: Matthew B. Ruby &amp; Ashley Rattenbury <br>
Speaker: Matthew B. Ruby (La Trobe University)
</p>

<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
Although plant-based diets are growing in popularity, there continues to be
widespread disagreement about their advantages and disadvantages,
particularly regarding sustainability. In a pre-registered study, we
investigated perceptions of the barriers and benefits of vegetarian diets,
dietary behavior, and beliefs about the environmental impact of meat eating
in an online Australian sample (n = 740). The most agreed upon barriers
were liking eating meat, one’s family eating meat, and limited choice when
eating out, and the most agreed upon benefits were eating more fruits and
vegetables, helping animals, and helping the environment, although the
impact of diet was perceived to be smaller than all other assessed pro-
environmental actions (e.g., recycling, using public transit). Mean
perceptions of barriers and benefits significantly predicted current meat
intake and willingness to reduce and eliminate meat intake. Results
suggest that advocacy groups can more effectively utilize environmental
arguments to promote plant-based diets.
</p>

