<h5>
Presentation 3: Motivated taste perception: Why do meat-eaters
expect vegan products to taste so bad?
</h5>

<p>
Authors: Daniel Rosenfeld &amp; A. Janet Tomiyama <br>
Speaker: Daniel Rosenfeld (University of California) </p>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
Vegan alternatives to animal-based foods are becoming increasingly
mainstream. Yet many meat-eaters remain biased against consuming
these products. Through a highly powered, preregistered study (n = 405),
we investigated meat-eaters’ expectations about the taste of vegan ice
cream. Meat-eaters expected vegan ice cream to taste substantially worse
than dairy ice cream tastes (d = 2.22), an effect partially explained by
perceptions that vegan ice cream is more unnatural and abnormal than
dairy ice cream is. Moderation analyses indicated that meat-eaters who
endorsed carnism more strongly or relied more heavily on the moral
foundation purity exhibited the greatest bias against vegan ice cream.
These findings suggest that meat-eaters may engage in motivated taste
perception, expecting vegan products to taste far worse than their animal-
based counterparts. Delegitimizing carnism and combating the perceptions
that vegan products are unnatural and abnormal offer promise for reducing
bias and increasing consumer acceptance of these products.
</p>

