<h5>Presentation 4: Barriers to meat reduction: Australians’ attitudes
towards vegetarian and vegans
</h5>
<p>
Authors: Hannibal Thai, Kelly S. Fielding, &amp; Winnifred R. Louis <br>
Speaker: Hannibal Thai (University of Queensland)</p>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
Two studies, a correlational survey (n = 550) and an experimental survey
(n = 500), explored barriers to meat reduction. The first study investigated a
mechanism underlying perceptions of vegetarians, i.e., whether
confirmation of ‘do-gooder’ stereotype (moralizing, and being judgmental)
leads to poor evaluation. A 2 (participant’s gender) x 2 (target’s diet) x 3
(stereotype confirmation) design found that vegetarian ‘do-gooder’ targets
were perceived to be more ethical and there was no negative impact of
their moralising on liking of the target. The correlational survey, drawing on
an Australian community sample, explored other potential barriers such as
personal and perceived societal attitudes to meat-free individuals. Having
more positive perceptions of meat-reducing individuals or vegetarians was
associated with higher willingness to reduce meat/animal
product consumption. These findings suggest that vegetarian individuals
who confirm stereotypes do not necessarily attract negative evaluations,
however, overall attitudes to vegetarians could deter reduction in meat
consumption.
</p>


